# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1917-world-series
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1917-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The **1883 major league baseball season** was contested from May 1 through September 30, 1883.
[src:1917-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] It was the second season for the American Association (AA) and eighth season for the National League (NL).
[src:1917-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Philadelphia Athletics won the AA pennant, while the Boston Beaneaters won the NL pennant.
[src:1917-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] There was no postseason, although there was a canceled exhibition series between the two pennant winners.
[src:1917-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the season, the Troy Trojans and Worcester Worcesters of the National League folded.
[src:1917-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] In its place, the league enfranchised two teams: the New York Gothams and Philadelphia Quakers (today's San Francisco Giants and Philadelphia Phillies).
[src:1917-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] It was decided that the six-team American Association would expand to eight teams and saw the minor league New York Metropolitans join and the enfranchisement of the Columbus Buckeyes.
[src:1917-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the season, the Boston Red Caps and St.
[src:1917-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Brown Stockings renamed as the Boston Beaneaters and St.
[src:1917-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The American Association and the National League, along with the Northwestern League, sign the Tripartite Agreement (also known as the National Agreement).
[src:1917-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] This agreement binds the leagues to respect each other's valid player contracts as well as increasing the size of the reserve list from 6 to 11 players.
[src:1917-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The 1883 schedule consisted of 98 games for all teams in the American Association and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:1917-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 14 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:1917-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] This format was unique to the 1883 season.
[src:1917-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Previously, the National League had played an 84-game schedule, with 12 games against each team being played, while a pre-expansion six-team American Association had played an 80-game schedule, with 16 games against each team being played.
[src:1917-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The following season would see the National League play a 112-game schedule (increase of 14 to 16 games each), while the American Association would expanded again, this time to twelve teams, for a 110-game schedule (of 10 games against each of the other eleven teams).
[src:1917-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on May 1 featuring all sixteen teams.
[src:1917-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] American Association would see its final day of the regular season on September 30 featuring four teams, while the National League would see its final day of the regular season on September 29, featuring all eight teams.
[src:1917-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] 6 tie games (1 in AA, 5 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:1917-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Louisville Eclipse and New York Metropolitans had one tie game each.
[src:1917-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Cleveland Blues and Detroit Wolverines had three tie games each.
[src:1917-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Buffalo Bisons and Philadelphia Quakers had one tie game each.
[src:1917-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Polo Grounds, home of the New York Metropolitans and Gothams, featured two baseball fields, at the southeast and southwest of the grounds.
[src:1917-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Gothams played entirely at the southeast grounds, while the Metropolitans moved alternated.
[src:1917-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The played ten games at the southeast diamond to start the season, before moving to the southwest diamond on May 30.
[src:1917-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The southwest diamond was of worse quality than the southeast diamond, so games at the southwest diamond did not last long.
[src:1917-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] They played only ten games (aside from a one-off at the southeast diamond on June 13) before returning to the southeast diamond in July.
[src:1917-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] They did play three more games at the southwest diamond on August 30, 31, and September 4 due to scheduling conflicts with the Gothams.
[src:1917-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Following a fire and a flood of their home at Exposition Park, the Pittsburgh Alleghenys had to move into a newly built venue, a second iteration of Exposition Park, which was built immediately south.
[src:1917-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] However, after only 17 games, they played their last game there on June 9 and returned to the first Exposition Park on June 12.
[src:1917-world-series/1883-new-york-gothams-season] The **1883 New York Gothams season** was the first professional baseball season played by the team now known as the **San Francisco Giants**.
[src:1917-world-series/1883-new-york-gothams-season] The team replaced the Troy Trojans when the National League awarded its franchise rights to John B.
[src:1917-world-series/1883-new-york-gothams-season] The team went 46–50, finishing in sixth place.
[src:1917-world-series/1884-new-york-gothams-season] The **1884 New York Gothams season** was the second season of that baseball franchise, eventually known as the San Francisco Giants.
[src:1917-world-series/1884-new-york-gothams-season] The team finished in fourth place, 22 games behind the pennant-winning Providence Grays.
[src:1917-world-series/1886-new-york-giants-season] The **1886 New York Giants season** was the franchise's fourth season.
[src:1917-world-series/1886-new-york-giants-season] The team had a record of 75–44, finishing third in the National League, 12.5 games behind the Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1917-world-series/1887-new-york-giants-season] The **1887 New York Giants season** was the franchise's fifth season.
[src:1917-world-series/1887-new-york-giants-season] The team finished in fourth place in the National League with a record of 68–55, 10+1⁄2 games behind the Detroit Wolverines.
[src:1917-world-series/1887-new-york-giants-season] The team amassed 415 stolen bases, the most for any team in the history of the National League.
[src:1917-world-series/1888-new-york-giants-season] The **1888 New York Giants season** was the franchise's sixth season.
[src:1917-world-series/1888-new-york-giants-season] Claiming six future Hall of Famers (Roger Connor, Mickey Welch, Buck Ewing, Tim Keefe, Jim O'Rourke, and John Montgomery Ward), the team won the National League pennant by nine games and defeated the St.
[src:1917-world-series/1888-new-york-giants-season] Keefe led the league in several major statistical categories, including wins, winning percentage, strikeouts, and earned run average.
[src:1917-world-series/1888-new-york-giants-season] The Giants beat the American Association champion St.
[src:1917-world-series/1888-new-york-giants-season] Louis Browns in the World Series, six games to four.
[src:1917-world-series/1917-world-series] The **1917** **World Series** was the championship series of Major League Baseball's (MLB) 1917 season.
[src:1917-world-series/1917-world-series] The 14th edition of the World Series, it was a best-of-seven playoff between the American League (AL) champion Chicago White Sox and the National League (NL) champion New York Giants.
[src:1917-world-series/1917-world-series] The White Sox won the series in six games.
[src:1917-world-series/1917-world-series] The series was played against the backdrop of World War I, which dominated American newspapers both that year and the next.
[src:1917-world-series/1917-world-series] The strong Chicago White Sox club finished the 1917 season with a 100–54 record, which remains their only 100-win season in franchise history to date.
[src:1917-world-series/1917-world-series] Their next World Series-winning team in 2005 finished the regular season with a 99–63 record.
[src:1917-world-series/1917-world-series] The Sox won Game 1 of the Series in Chicago 2–1 behind a complete game by Eddie Cicotte.
[src:1917-world-series/1917-world-series] Happy Felsch hit a home run in the fourth inning that provided the winning margin.
[src:1917-world-series/1917-world-series] In Game 2 the Sox beat the Giants 7–2 behind another complete game effort by Red Faber to take a 2–0 lead in the Series.
[src:1917-world-series/1917-world-series] Back in New York for Game 3, Cicotte again threw a complete game, but the Sox could not muster a single run against Giants' starter Rube Benton and lost 2–0.
[src:1917-world-series/1917-world-series] In Game 4 the Sox were shut out again 5–0 by Ferdie Schupp.
[src:1917-world-series/1917-world-series] Faber threw another complete game, but the Series was even at 2–2 going back to Chicago.
[src:1917-world-series/1917-world-series] Reb Russell started Game 5 in Chicago, but only faced three batters before giving way to Cicotte.
[src:1917-world-series/1917-world-series] Going into the bottom of the seventh inning, Chicago was down 5–2, but they rallied to score three in the seventh and three in the eighth to win 8–5.
[src:1917-world-series/1917-world-series] Faber pitched the final two innings for the win.
[src:1917-world-series/1917-world-series] In Game 6 the Sox took an early 3–0 lead and on the strength of another complete-game victory from Faber (his third of the Series) won 4–2 and clinched the World Championship.
[src:1917-world-series/1917-world-series] Eddie Collins was the hitting hero, batting .409 over the six-game series while Cicotte and Faber combined to pitch 50 out of a total 52 World Series innings to lead the staff.
[src:1917-world-series/1917-world-series] The decisive game underscored the Giants' post-season frustrations, featuring a famous rundown in which Giants' third baseman Heinie Zimmerman futilely chased the speedy Eddie Collins toward home plate with what would be the Series-winning run.
[src:1917-world-series/1917-world-series] Catcher Bill Rariden had run up the third base line to start a rundown, expecting pitcher Rube Benton or first baseman Walter Holke to cover the plate.
[src:1917-world-series/1917-world-series] However, neither of them budged, forcing Zimmerman to chase Collins while pawing helplessly in the air with the ball in an attempt to tag him.
[src:1917-world-series/1917-world-series] Two years before the issue of baseball betting reached its peak, Zimmerman found himself having to publicly deny purposely allowing the run to score, i.e. to deny that he had "thrown" the game.
[src:1917-world-series/1917-world-series] In truth, McGraw blamed Benton and Holke for failing to cover the plate.
[src:1917-world-series/1917-world-series] Zimmerman would eventually be banned for life due to various accusations of corruption.
[src:1917-world-series/1917-world-series] The White Sox, who were essentially dismantled following the 1920 season by baseball commissioner Kenesaw Mountain Landis due to the Black Sox Scandal in the 1919 World Series, did not make it to another World Series until 1959, and did not win another World Series until 2005.
[src:1917-world-series/1917-world-series] This was the first of nine meetings between teams from Chicago and New York City for a major professional sports championship.
[src:1917-world-series/1917-world-series] Fred McMullin drove in Chicago's first run, and Happy Felsch's homer made it 2–0.
[src:1917-world-series/1917-world-series] Giants pitcher Slim Sallee knocked in his side's only run with a single after a Lew McCarty triple.
[src:1917-world-series/1917-world-series] Shoeless Joe Jackson's two-run single capped a five-run fourth inning for the White Sox, who knocked out Giants starter Ferdie Schupp in the second inning.
[src:1917-world-series/1917-world-series] The home team won for the third straight time as the series moved to New York.
[src:1917-world-series/1917-world-series] The only runs of a snappy 1 hour, 55 minute game came on a Dave Robertson triple, Walter Holke double and a single by George Burns.
[src:1917-world-series/1917-world-series] The first of a pair of homers by Giants center fielder Benny Kauff was an inside-the-park one that sailed over Sox center fielder Happy Felsch's head.
[src:1917-world-series/1917-world-series] The other came in the eighth off Chicago reliever Dave Danforth.
[src:1917-world-series/1917-world-series] Even though Red Faber would start Games 4 and 6, he was brought in from the bullpen to close Game 5.
[src:1917-world-series/1917-world-series] Taking no chances, the Sox yanked starter Reb Russell after just three batters, all of whom reached base.
[src:1917-world-series/1917-world-series] A three-error third inning behind Eddie Cicotte put the Giants up 4–1.
[src:1917-world-series/1917-world-series] But after a game-tying rally in the seventh, the Sox won it in the eighth as Happy Felsch greeted reliever Pol Perritt with an RBI single.
[src:1917-world-series/1917-world-series] It was the fifth straight win by the home team in this Series.
[src:1917-world-series/1917-world-series] A pair of errors proved costly to the Giants in a three-run fourth when Chick Gandil and Ray Schalk followed with RBI hits.
[src:1917-world-series/1917-world-series] New York's hopes rose with a Buck Herzog triple in the next inning that made it 3–2.
[src:1917-world-series/1917-world-series] But with the workhorse Faber holding the Giants at bay the rest of the way, the Sox got an insurance run in the ninth on hits by Buck Weaver and Nemo Leibold, and the Series was theirs.
[src:1917-world-series/1917-world-series] It would be their last championship until 2005.
[src:1917-world-series/giants-season] The **1885 New York Giants season** was the franchise's third season.
[src:1917-world-series/giants-season] The team finished in second place, 2 games behind the Chicago White Stockings.
